latest news.eng_title: Inside the luxury capsule carrying passengers to the edge of space
latest news.summary: Space Perspective's Spaceship Neptune - Excelsior craft successfully completed a test flight, reaching an altitude of 100,000 feet without a crew. The balloon capsule will carry up to eight passengers to the edge of space, offering a luxurious experience with world-class food and beverage, comfortable seating, and amenities. The company plans to start human spaceflights in 2025 and commercial operations in 2026, with over 1,800 tickets already sold. According to Taber MacCallum, founder and chief technology officer, 'This uncrewed flight not only proves our technology but also brings us closer to making space accessible for everyone.' The market for space tourism is expected to reach over £3 billion by 2030, with companies like SpaceX and Virgin Galactic leading the way in making space travel more accessible and affordable.
latest news.title: Inside the luxury capsule carrying passengers to the edge of space

latest news.eng_title: Thales Alenia Space Faces Job Cuts Amid Competition from SpaceX
latest news.summary: Approximately 700 employees of Thales Alenia Space (TAS) gathered in front of the Toulouse site on September 17, 2024, to protest the company's plan to eliminate 1,237 positions in Europe. This includes 650 positions (out of 2,700) in Toulouse and 330 positions (out of 1,800) in Cannes. Éric Peyrat, a representative of the FO union, stated, 'We don't want to become like Boeing, where they can't even screw in a bolt.' He believes that the company's plan to separate its lowest-paid employees and outsource work is a real threat to the company's expertise. According to Peyrat, the company's decision to reduce its workforce is likely a result of the competition from SpaceX's Starlink constellation, which has reduced the company's client base by half in three years. The company's management explained that they are redeploying employees within the group due to the 'undercharge' caused by Starlink. However, Éric Peyrat believes that the company's overall health could allow it to weather the storm, as the company's order books are full until the end of 2026. The unions are playing a waiting game, as the European works council of Thales has blocked any negotiations by refusing to give its opinion on the plan to eliminate positions.
latest news.title: Toulouse : Thales Alenia Space veut garder ses emplois

latest news.eng_title: Morgan Stanley sees more downside for Virgin Galactic stock, slashes price target
latest news.summary: Morgan Stanley has significantly reduced its price target for Virgin Galactic from $35.00 to $5.00 per share, citing ongoing challenges and a lack of near-term catalysts for the stock. The investment bank notes that Virgin Galactic's commercial flight hiatus, expected to last until 2026, has led to an 85% year-to-date decline in the stock's value. Morgan Stanley's analysts are skeptical about the company's ability to meet its ambitious goals for the Delta-class spaceships, which are central to its long-term revenue projections. The firm's revised outlook incorporates greater conservatism in its forecasts, with the expectation that SPCE will not see positive adjusted EBITDA until 2028 and positive free cash flow until 2029. According to Morgan Stanley, 'the stock's YTD slide (down ~85%) reflects the realization that the business model / attractive economics are premised on delivering a new fleet on schedule and at cost.'
latest news.title: Morgan Stanley sees more downside for Virgin Galactic stock, slashes price target

latest news.eng_title: SpaceX Starlink has 2,500 aircraft under contract after United megadeal, director says
latest news.summary: SpaceX has nearly doubled its backlog of Starlink in-flight Wi-Fi orders with the recent United Airlines deal, according to Nick Galano, SpaceX director of Starlink aviation sales and partnerships. Galano stated, 'Very excited that we have about 2,500 aircraft under contract now, bringing what was effectively a startup to now what we think is a growing experience that's going to resonate with all the passengers and the airlines worldwide.' The deal with United will see over 1,000 planes retrofitted with Starlink, a service that will be offered for free to passengers.

latest news.eng_title: SpaceX Starlink has 2,500 airplanes under contract after United megadeal, director says
latest news.summary: SpaceX has secured a major deal with United Airlines, which will see the airline outfit its over 1,000 planes with Starlink in-flight Wi-Fi. According to Nick Galano, SpaceX director of Starlink aviation sales and partnerships, this deal nearly doubles the company's backlog of Starlink orders, bringing the total to 2,500 aircraft under contract. Galano emphasized the 'sheer factor of the capacity that we can provide' via Starlink, which is 'probably over 100 times what all the legacy systems have provided.' SpaceX is also working to simplify the installation process, aiming to complete it in under a day. This is in contrast to Delta Air Lines, which takes an average of three days to retrofit its satellite IFC systems. Delta's managing director of in-flight entertainment and connectivity, Glenn Latta, noted that the airline's process is more intensive due to the need to remove the existing system and install a new one.

latest news.eng_title: Virgin Galactic shares target cut by Morgan Stanley, maintains Underweight tag By Investing.com
latest news.summary: Morgan Stanley has reduced Virgin Galactic's price target from $35.00 to $5.00 and maintained its Underweight rating on the stock. The adjustment follows Virgin Galactic's announcement that commercial flights will be on hold until approximately 2026. The company's stock has decreased by 85% year-to-date due to growing investor concerns about the feasibility of its business model and the economic attractiveness of its plans. Morgan Stanley's commentary highlights the challenges Virgin Galactic faces, including adhering to its fleet delivery schedule and managing costs effectively. Despite facing financial hurdles, Virgin Galactic has a strong financial position, with a robust cash reserve and a market cap of $203.94 million. The company projects substantial revenue growth, with an annual revenue target of $450 million and possibly reaching $2 billion as its fleet and spaceports expand.

latest news.eng_title: SpaceX's Starlink Dominance Raises Concerns About the Future of Space Exploration
latest news.summary: SpaceX, led by Elon Musk, has reached a symbolic milestone with the launch of its 7,000th Starlink satellite. However, this achievement highlights the company's dominance in the satellite market, with over 62% of active satellites in orbit belonging to SpaceX. This translates to over 6,000 Starlink satellites out of a total of 10,000 in orbit. Other players in the market, such as OneWeb and Kuiper, have significantly fewer satellites, with OneWeb having 631 active satellites and Kuiper having a mere 200. The Chinese government's Guowang project aims to launch 13,000 satellites, rivaling Starlink's presence. The European consortium, composed of Airbus Defence and Space, Eutelsat, SES, and Thales Alenia Space, is also working on a similar project. The dominance of Starlink raises questions about the implications for the future of space exploration and the potential consequences for the environment, including light pollution and the risk of collisions. As the space race continues, SpaceX has announced plans to launch even more satellites, with over a dozen constellations in the works.

news knowledge.eng_title: Blue Origin to Launch Eighth Commercial Suborbital Flight on August 29

Organization: University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill

news knowledge.summary: Blue Origin is set to launch its eighth commercial suborbital flight on August 29, 2024. The flight, designated NS-26, will carry six passengers, including Nicolina Elrick, Rob Ferl, Eugene Grin, Eiman Jahangir, Karsen Kitchen, and Ephraim Rabin. Karsen Kitchen, a 21-year-old student from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, will become the youngest woman to reach the edge of space, a feat previously achieved by Anastatia Mayers, who flew on a Virgin Galactic spacecraft in August 2023. The flight will last around 10-12 minutes, during which time the passengers will experience weightlessness and see the curvature of the Earth. The exact cost of a seat on the New Shepard spacecraft is not publicly disclosed. The launch will be broadcast live on Blue Origin's website, and the flight will be followed by a press conference. According to Blue Origin, the company has made significant improvements to the New Shepard spacecraft, including enhanced safety features and a more efficient propulsion system. The company has also announced plans to offer commercial flights to the edge of space, with prices starting at $200,000 per seat.

news knowledge.eng_title: Virgin Galactic Unveils New Spaceplane Delta for Suborbital Flights
news knowledge.summary: Virgin Galactic has unveiled the design of its new spaceplane, Delta, which is designed for suborbital flights. The spaceplane is expected to carry tourists to an altitude of approximately 80 km above the Earth's surface, offering a breathtaking view of the planet. Virgin Galactic claims that the new spaceplane will be able to make flights with passengers on board every three days, a significant improvement over the previous VSS Unity, which could only make one flight per month. The Delta spaceplane will have a capacity of six passengers, compared to four on the VSS Unity. The company plans to start using the Delta spaceplane in 2026 and expects to generate $450 million in revenue from space tourism annually. Virgin Galactic has accelerated the design process this year and has begun manufacturing components for the spaceplane, with assembly and testing expected to follow soon.

news knowledge.eng_title: Virgin Galactic Unveils New Spaceplane Delta with Increased Capacity and Reduced Flight Time
news knowledge.summary: Virgin Galactic has unveiled a new video showcasing the design of its upcoming spaceplane, Delta. The company claims that Delta will increase the number of passengers from four to six and reduce the time between flights from a month to just three days. The new spaceplane is equipped with a hybrid rocket system and is expected to enter commercial operation in 2026. According to Michael Colglazier, CEO of Virgin Galactic, 'We have made significant progress in the second quarter in the realization of our Delta spacecraft program, the pace of completing the design has accelerated, and the production of tools has begun.' The company plans to generate $450 million in revenue per year for several years after the introduction of the first two Delta spacecraft. The video also outlines plans to deploy up to five spacecraft at launch sites around the world in the future. 'In the next month, our teams will focus on the assembly and testing of our production spacecraft, which will enter commercial operation in 2026,' Colglazier added.

news knowledge.eng_title: Get a sneak peek at Virgin Galactic's new Delta class space plane (video)
news knowledge.summary: Virgin Galactic has unveiled the design for its new Delta class spaceship, a sleek and modular spacecraft that aims to provide new efficiencies for human spaceflight. The Delta ships are being built to operate with an average turnaround time of just three days, a significant breakthrough that would structurally change the cost of human spaceflight. The new spacecraft will also upgrade from four passengers to six and is set to fly for the first time no earlier than 2026. According to CEO Michael Colglazier, 'Progress on our Delta Class spaceship program was substantial in Q2, with the pace of design completion accelerating and tool fabrication underway.' The company plans to generate revenue of $450 million per year in the years following the first two Delta spaceships entering service. Virgin Galactic has also completed a new Delta space plane manufacturing facility in Mesa, Arizona, marking a major milestone in its new generation spaceship plans.

news knowledge.eng_title: Virgin Galactic Unveils Ambitious Financial Models for New Spaceplane Line
news knowledge.summary: Virgin Galactic presented ambitious financial models for its new line of suborbital spaceplanes, Delta class, at the annual report conference on August 7. The company plans to conduct 125 space flights per year with 6 passengers on each vehicle, transporting 750 people annually at an average ticket price of $600,000, generating $450 million in revenue. After accounting for expenses, Virgin Galactic expects to generate a net income of $95-110 million per year. The company also considers the possibility of adding a second spaceport, possibly in Europe or the Middle East, which would increase the number of flights to 275 per year, generating $990 million in revenue and a net income of $450-500 million per year. These financial models are based on several assumptions, including sufficient demand for high-priced space flights. Virgin Galactic's own research, as well as research by Credit Suisse and Jeffries Global Research, estimate a global addressable market of 300,000 people, growing at 8% annually. The company currently has around 700 customers. Virgin Galactic is just beginning the transition from designing spaceplanes to production, working with Bell Textron and Qarbon Aerospace to produce key sections of the vehicles. Final assembly will be done at a new factory in Mesa, Arizona. The company expects to receive the first components from its suppliers in the first half of 2025 and plans to roll out and test the first ship in the second half of the year. 'It will take several years before we start flights at the second spaceport,' said Michael Colglazier, CEO of Virgin Galactic, mentioning the development of the spaceport itself and necessary regulatory approvals. He suggested that 2025 is the window when the company can start discussing the launch of a new spaceport. news knowledge.eng_title: Virgin Galactic outlines economics of its future spaceplanes
news knowledge.summary: Virgin Galactic outlined its financial models for its new Delta-class spaceplanes, which are expected to enter commercial service in 2026. According to the company's projections, the spaceplanes will generate $450 million in revenue in the first year, with adjusted earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization (EBITDA) of $95 million to $110 million. In an 'expanded fleet' model, with four spaceships and two mothership aircraft, Virgin Galactic estimates it can perform 275 flights a year, generating $990 million in revenue and adjusted EBITDA of $450 million to $500 million. The company also examined adding a second spaceport, which it projects will generate $1.98 billion in revenue and adjusted EBITDA of $1 billion to $1.1 billion. The financial models rest on several assumptions, including sufficient demand and the ability to build and operate the Delta-class vehicles at projected costs.

news knowledge.eng_title: Virgin Galactic Reports Progress on Delta-Class Spacecraft and Optimistic Financial Outlook
news knowledge.summary: Virgin Galactic (NYSE: SPCE) reported significant progress in the development of its Delta-class spacecraft and provided an optimistic financial outlook during its second-quarter 2024 earnings call. The company is on track to complete the design phase of its Delta-class spacecraft and transition to construction and testing, with the ultimate goal of launching commercial operations in 2026. Virgin Galactic expects to generate substantial revenue in the early stages of its commercial spaceflight operations, projecting annual revenue of $450 million with its initial fleet and potentially reaching $2 billion as its fleet and spaceports expand. The company also reported a solid financial position, with $394 million raised through stock offerings and a strong cash reserve. Key takeaways include the company's progress with its Delta-class spacecraft program, its plan to initiate commercial spaceflight operations in 2026, and its focus on customer experience and efficient spaceflight systems. Virgin Galactic has also raised substantial capital to support the development of its fleet and has a robust cash reserve. The company is actively managing supply chain issues and has seen success and demand for its research flights. According to CFO Doug Ahrens, the company expects 2024 to be its highest year of spending, with peak activity in late 2023 and early 2024. Virgin Galactic continues to be committed to achieving high-frequency, high-significance, and high-profit commercial spaceflights, with a focus on scaling its fleet and improving customer experience. The company's current financial position and strategic investments suggest a confident outlook for the future, despite some challenges in operating expenses and cash flow.

news knowledge.eng_title: Virgin Galactic Announces Second Quarter 2024 Financial Results And Provides Business Update
news knowledge.summary: Virgin Galactic Holdings, Inc. has announced its financial results for the second quarter ended June 30, 2024. The company reported a net loss of $93.8 million, compared to a net loss of $134.4 million in the second quarter of 2023. Revenue was $4.2 million, up from $1.9 million in the second quarter of 2023. The company's cash position remains strong, with $821 million in cash, cash equivalents, and marketable securities as of June 30, 2024. Michael Colglazier, Chief Executive Officer of Virgin Galactic, said, 'Progress on our Delta Class spaceship program was substantial in Q2, with the pace of design completion accelerating and tool fabrication underway.' The company's production schedule for the Delta Class spaceships remains on track for commercial service in 2026. Virgin Galactic expects free cash flow for the third quarter of 2024 to be in the range of $(115) million to $(125) million.
